  "prompt": "Why does acetone break down cell membranes?",
  "response": "Acetone is a polar organic solvent that can disrupt cell membranes primarily through its interaction with lipid components. Cell membranes are composed chiefly of a lipid bilayer, which consists of phospholipids with hydrophobic (water-repellent) tails and hydrophilic (water-attracting) heads. \n\nWhen acetone comes into contact with the cell membrane, it can dissolve the lipids due to its solvent properties. This dissolving effect disrupts the structural integrity of the lipid bilayer, causing the membrane to lose its cohesion and functionality. The disruption of the lipid bilayer leads to increased permeability, allowing substances that normally wouldn't penetrate the membrane to enter the cell, which can result in cell damage or death.\n\nAdditionally, acetone can denature proteins and other membrane-bound components, further compromising the cell membrane's structure and function. This breakdown of the cell membrane is why acetone is commonly used in laboratory settings to permeabilize cells for various biochemical applications.",
